Notebook[{
Cell["Coordinatization Tutorial", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"e893989b-8dc8-4aa0-ba5a-0e9bf09987fa"],

Cell["\<\
Two ways to attach numerical coordinates to graph vertices: spatial radar \
coordinates (vector of distances to a basis), and orthogonal coordinates \
(signed displacements along chosen axes). Both reduce vertex labels to \
numbers an infra-observer can compute by walking.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6ac979d6-bdd2-46b8-8db1-8ae84142c1ff"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c8f7ae62-2408-41d1-8fe4-76ecf1146a15"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"03ea9eb5-b4ea-4fc7-9b95-24b42c93f3f4"],

Cell["Spatial radar coordinates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"21c29505-d066-490a-bc2d-61d50ab19b42"],

Cell["\<\
A radar basis is a vertex set such that every vertex has a unique distance \
vector to the basis. Once chosen, the radar coordinate of a vertex is exactly \
that distance vector.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3b446ec5-efe4-4bef-a7d0-2f3072693e3f"],

Cell["Find a small radar basis on a grid:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"46e13fec-e9b7-4c5f-85e9-0c9b4cb26af4"],

Cell["g = GridGraph[{3, 3}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"bb4f9927-4455-49a7-a703-e3ccf55d19eb"],

Cell["FindRadarBasis[g, 1]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"b62840f9-6238-461d-b508-a0bd8b82b80b"],

Cell["Test that a candidate is a radar basis:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"379fc867-0d84-48eb-b3d9-361826403d24"],

Cell["RadarBasisQ[g, {1, 9}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"dce3e118-9ff5-40f9-a652-f538b8911863"],

Cell["\<\
The radar coordinate of every vertex with respect to the basis {1, 9}:\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"0c778fe9-796b-42f9-8491-bc30f646c2b6"],

Cell["RadarCoordinates[g, {1, 9}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"65bff8ae-9ae2-4b5b-9ee9-39e18a41837a"],

Cell["Equivalent for a single vertex:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"4374961f-ac9b-43ab-ac88-655e49c1f173"],

Cell["RadarCoordinates[g, 5, {1, 9}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"09cfc2ee-49f0-4334-8b9f-4e287971c78a"],

Cell["Orthogonal coordinates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"58ed310b-29c5-415c-b770-b3fc78f3673a"],

Cell["\<\
Pick a small set of well-separated longest paths (or DAGs) as axes; project \
each vertex onto each axis and take the layer index. The result is a tuple of \
non-negative integers (or signed integers, when an origin is chosen).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4913ecb3-6415-4c28-874b-bc0a88e21c04"],

Cell["\<\
Find two orthogonal axes through the centre vertex 5 of a 3x3 grid:\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"ee363d22-a41c-4158-a383-4579b9ba434b"],

Cell["axes = FindOrthogonalAxes[g, 5, 2]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"eab3dce8-b44a-4351-89a9-5ccab226501f"],

Cell["\<\
Coordinates of vertex 1 with respect to those axes (vertex 5 plays the role \
of origin):\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"0167ddff-626b-43d8-9059-4cc5543d899b"],

Cell["OrthogonalCoordinates[g, 5, 1]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"31c4dac9-9ddc-4255-8059-a826433d22c7"],

Cell["Bulk form: every vertex's coordinate as an Association.", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"8e409df1-6484-424f-95bd-d6e706688df8"],

Cell["OrthogonalCoordinates[g, 5]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"8a78f71f-9185-4818-91c0-5a0bd252f8fe"],

Cell["Selecting a coordinate when the projection is multi-valued", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a0190bec-2e17-49ce-8497-c9203c21b776"],

Cell["\<\
When several axis vertices are equidistant from v, the projection ties. The \
SelectCoordinate option (default First) picks one value from the tied list.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a34e9ec5-c2d2-4838-b1c4-538fa5eb0574"],

Cell["\<\
A 4-cycle: vertex 4 is equidistant from vertex 1 and vertex 3 along the axis \
{1, 2, 3}. Position 0 (= vertex 1) and position 2 (= vertex 3) both tie.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"6ccf73dd-882c-454a-9b3e-3eeba2595458"],

Cell["c4 = CycleGraph[4]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"8f43fe6d-7a06-4aff-8211-240d1c6e200d"],

Cell["\<\
{OrthogonalCoordinates[c4, {{1, 2, 3}}, 4, \"SelectCoordinate\" -> First], \
OrthogonalCoordinates[c4, {{1, 2, 3}}, 4, \"SelectCoordinate\" -> Last], \
OrthogonalCoordinates[c4, {{1, 2, 3}}, 4, \"SelectCoordinate\" -> All]}\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"8cb2e935-1091-48a0-b07a-3e67a608661f"],

Cell["\<\
First gives 0, Last gives 2, All preserves the tied list {0, 2}. You can also \
pass any function on lists (e.g. Mean, Median, or Quantile[#, 0.25] &).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ed6a870f-f556-460e-a0ca-9f7e29999bbb"],

Cell["InfraPoint multi-vertex centre", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d5595a33-ccfe-4eff-bfa6-d4566565980c"],

Cell["\<\
The centre can be specified as InfraPoint[{v1, v2, ...}], in which case each \
axis is required to contain at least one of the listed vertices as an \
interior point. The axis is signed relative to the first such vertex.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7712e12b-169f-4117-87e1-258e1acff79d"],

Cell["FindOrthogonalAxes[g, InfraPoint[{1, 5}], 2]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"ce77c56a-1006-4e01-837f-a014eff6de4c"],

Cell["Where this connects to the rest of the paclet", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"3db9f2f4-304d-4b51-afd2-845d2b3bca84"],

Cell["\<\
The Projective layer's pencil at O picks out one canonical line per \
direction. If those lines are taken as axes, OrthogonalCoordinates assigns \
each vertex a tuple in Z^k -- the projective affinization map (planned, see \
ProjectivePrimitivesRoster). The Coordinatization layer is the metric \
scaffolding for that construction.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"acf50ef2-172f-47c2-a116-62f56045436b"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"80c140e9-3519-485a-9635-b092896aef30"],

Cell["CoordinatizationGuide -- categorical overview.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"3ab111a4-0964-4f74-a51a-ee5e27c7f655"],

Cell["\<\
EuclideanLayerTutorial -- the metric primitives FindSegment / FindLine that \
orthogonal projections rely on.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"1c2a765f-513b-48d8-941d-4589cd0e6311"],

Cell["ProjectiveLayerTutorial -- pencils as axis sources.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"88193144-8a25-4b1f-a061-744d3f48e35f"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"5cfadcb1-9e04-48f7-97b6-2716c21d9663"],

Cell["\<\
Slater, Leaves of Trees, Congressus Numerantium 14, 549-559, 1975 (origin of \
resolving sets / metric dimension).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"49024e1b-5452-477d-9d62-4c6672903d4b"],

Cell["\<\
Chartrand, Eroh, Johnson and Oellermann, Resolvability in Graphs and the \
Metric Dimension of a Graph, Discrete Appl. Math. 105, 99-113, 2000.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c1408383-b25b-4747-9b05-e6b8360a23d4"]
},
FrontEndVersion->"14.3 for Mac OS X ARM (64-bit) (July 8, 2025)",
